# Animation Selection Rules

## Default Preference: `react-native-ease` for basic animations

When you need basic state-driven animations (fade/slide/scale/enter-exit), prefer `react-native-ease` over `react-native-reanimated` because Ease uses native platform animation APIs and is designed to be lightweight and simple.  
Docs: [react-native-ease](https://github.com/AppAndFlow/react-native-ease)

### Use Ease for these cases

- Fade/opacity transitions (show/hide via boolean)
- Simple slide/translate/scale transitions driven by state
- Enter/exit transitions (mount/unmount or conditional rendering)
- Interruptible animations when the target state changes continuously (Ease redirects to the new target rather than jumping)
- Timing or spring transitions with explicit configuration (`transition.type: 'timing' | 'spring' | 'none'`)

### Basic usage (conceptual)

- Use `animate={{ ... }}` to define target values
- Use `initialAnimate={{ ... }}` if you want to animate from initial values on mount
- Use `transition={{ type: 'timing' | 'spring', duration?, easing?, damping?, stiffness?, mass?, delay?, loop? }}` to control the feel
- Use `transition={{ type: 'none' }}` to apply values immediately

## Use Reanimated for advanced / gesture-driven animations

Only use `react-native-reanimated` when you need capabilities that Ease is not optimized for or does not support.

### Use Reanimated when:

- Gesture-driven animations (pan/pinch/drag) with continuous input
- Complex interpolations & chaining beyond “animate-to-target”
- Layout animations (width/height/layout animated as layout changes)  
- Shared element transitions (between screens/routes)
- Use cases that require Reanimated shared values/worklets and deeper Reanimated architecture

## Non-goals / Limitations of Ease (to avoid picking the wrong tool)

Per the docs of `react-native-ease`, Ease is not intended for:

- Complex gesture-driven animations
- Layout animations
- Shared element transitions

If you are considering one of the above, prefer Reanimated.

## Runtime Requirements (to avoid surprises)

Ease requires a compatible runtime environment (Fabric / new arch). Before adopting it widely, verify requirements in the docs:  
[react-native-ease requirements](https://github.com/AppAndFlow/react-native-ease)

## Codebase Rules

- On the same UI surface (same component/view), prefer a single animation engine to avoid overlapping/competing animation behavior.
- If the animation is only opacity/transform driven by state: default to Ease.
- If it involves layout/shared-element transitions or gesture worklets: default to Reanimated.

## Migration Helper Skill (if applicable)

If you already have many basic animations implemented with `react-native-reanimated` or the legacy React Native `Animated` API, consider using the existing skill:

- [`react-native-ease-refactor`](.agents/skills/react-native-ease-refactor/SKILL.md) (migration for basic animations) 

Use it when migrating patterns that match “basic transitions” (fade/slide/scale/enter-exit) across the codebase. Keep Reanimated for gesture-driven, layout, or shared-element transitions.
